Lessons that can be learned from the Cuban Crisis today
"Thirteen Days" (formerly "Dreizehn Tage"), a new film about the Cuban Crisis, will soon be released in cinemas of many countries.
Everyone should see this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events – particularly regarding controversies surrounding a US national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy convened his closest advisors at the White House.
Aerial photographs of the region had revealed the construction of a station for atomic weapons on Cuba.
The decisions made in the following thirteen days, and those to which we could not bring ourselves, could have led to the outbreak of an atomic war.
The film illustrates what took place at the White House during those days.
Recordings made during Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
After the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard convened a discussion roundtable to discuss both the film and the crisis it addresses.
Participants in this round included, among others: Robert McNamara, the Secretary of Defense under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a history professor at Harvard who wrote a book about the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a political science professor at Harvard who presented a classic study on the Cuban Missile Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision," thirty years ago.
Moreover, Peter A. Almond, the producer of the film, was present.
Despite various criticisms of the filmic treatment of the topic, the discussion participants could agree that the movie portrays the problems and the pressure with which President Kennedy was confronted precisely as they were in reality.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized it as follows:
Advisors must play their role in the event of a crisis, but ultimately, it is solely the president who bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors - both civilian and military - wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his persistent questions were alternatives and hazards revealed that were essential in determining the consequences.
It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; additionally, the communication lines must be kept open.
To translate the given German sentence into English, I will break it down into smaller parts and then reconstruct it in English while maintaining its original meaning and structure.  German sentence: "Einen Gegner in die Enge zu treiben, ohne dass diplomatische Kanäle frei gehalten werden, die einem das Verständnis der gegnerischen Lage ermöglichen, könnte sich als verhängnisvoll erweisen."  Step-by-step translation:  1. "Einen Gegner in die Enge zu treiben" - To drive an opponent into a corner 2. "ohne dass" - without 3. "diplomatische Kanäle frei gehalten werden" - diplomatic channels being kept open 4. "die einem das Verständnis der gegnerischen Lage ermöglichen" - which allow one to understand the opponent's situation 5. "könnte sich als verhängnisvoll erweisen" - could prove detrimental  Putting it all together, the English translation is:  "To drive an opponent into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open, which allow one to understand the opponent's situation, could prove detrimental."
The United States relies on allies.
Kennedy therefore acted this way because the NATO alliance, other allies, and the opinion of the world supported him.
A certain period of time is necessary for making good decisions.
When it comes to life and death, a politician cannot allow the media to pressure him into acting.
The fact that a week passed during which all involved factors were examined and weighed as precisely as possible was crucial for the result.
But would such a temporal margin for weighing options still exist today given the currently existing mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it is necessary to put oneself in the opponent's shoes.
In one of the many-criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to an enthusiastic admiral that the naval blockade Kennedy had imposed on Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's resolve, and not as a means to halt certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted with more calmness?
After all, the USA had also stationed nuclear warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba merely reflected this policy.   Note: "Chruschtschows" is typically spelled "Khrushchev" in English. This is a common name in English texts referring to the former Soviet leader.
However, Kennedy appeared fearful regarding the consequences that the stationing of Soviet rockets in Cuba could have had for Berlin.
The pressure of atomic weapons on Cuba would have further endangered the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
Ultimately, "the Berlin crisis was resolved by the results of the Cuba crisis," according to the claim of historian Ernest May.
"The phrase 'soon it will be too late' was a commonly heard argument that Kennedy received from his advisors."
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba while the rockets, as they assumed, were en route to Cuba via sea.
An army of about 180,000 U.S. troops was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a blitz bombing campaign that would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack on Kosovo sixty years later. "I needed thirty years," McNamara said, "to find out that there were already nuclear weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and 90 of them strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He asked Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew about it."
And I explicitly recommended that atomic weapons be used.
The translation of the given German sentence to English is:  "I knew that this would have led to the annihilation of Cuba."
Castro and, to a greater extent, his comrade Che Guevara were willing to see Cuba reduced to ashes, so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!
An invasion would, under certain circumstances, have resulted in the deaths of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because Kennedy's government lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (which is more common when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is convinced that an invasion would "certainly" have led to a Soviet atomic attack on the USA.
Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military in Cuba was limited: despite explicit contrary orders from the chairman, U2 aircraft flying over Cuban airspace were shot down.
A difficult question to answer, which did not come up during this debate at Harvard, is the following: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Khrushchev, who distinguished himself more through rational behavior during the crisis, but rather an opponent of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong-il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the spread of atomic weapons, this danger could one day become reality.
The discussions today about a limited missile defense and the threat of atomic blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in the light of this terrible but decidedly realistic idea.
Harvard has launched a new website on the internet where key documents regarding the Cuban Missile Crisis as well as current atomic threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
